The reversible (isothermal) work for an ideal gas expanding from the initial state \((P_{1},V_{1})\) to the final pressure \(P_{2}\) is  

\[
w_{\text{rev}}=-nRT\ln\frac{P_{2}}{P_{1}}
\]

---

**1. Amount of substance**

\[
n=\frac{m}{M_{\text{CH}_4}}=\frac{4.50\;\text{g}}{16.04\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}=0.2805\;\text{mol}
\]

**2. Initial pressure**

\[
P_{1}= \frac{nRT}{V_{1}}
      =\frac{(0.2805\;\text{mol})(8.314\;\text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1})(310\;\text{K})}
             {12.7\;\text{dm}^{3}\times10^{-3}\;\text{m}^{3}\text{dm}^{-3}}
      =5.69\times10^{4}\;\text{Pa}=0.562\;\text{atm}
\]

**3. Final pressure (assumed external pressure)**  

Take the external pressure as \(P_{2}=1.00\;\text{atm}=1.01325\times10^{5}\;\text{Pa}\).

**4. Reversible work**

\[
\begin{aligned}
w_{\text{rev}} &=-nRT\ln\frac{P_{2}}{P_{1}}\\[4pt]
               &=-\bigl(0.2805\;\text{mol}\bigr)(8.314\;\text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1})(310\;\text{K})
                 \ln\!\left(\frac{1.00\;\text{atm}}{0.562\;\text{atm}}\right)\\[4pt]
               &=-722.9\;\text{J}\;\times\;0.577\\[4pt]
               &=-4.17\times10^{2}\;\text{J}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\boxed{-4.17\times10^{2}}\ \text{J}
\]

The reaction is  

\[
\mathrm{Mg(s)}+2\;\mathrm{HCl(aq)}\rightarrow \mathrm{MgCl_2(aq)}+\mathrm{H_2(g)}
\]

Moles of Mg  

\[
n_{\text{Mg}}=\frac{15\;\text{g}}{24.305\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}=0.617\;\text{mol}
\]

From the stoichiometry, \(n_{\mathrm{H_2}} = n_{\text{Mg}} = 0.617\;\text{mol}\).

At constant external pressure (1 atm) the volume change due to the produced gas is  

\[
\Delta V = \frac{n_{\mathrm{H_2}}RT}{P}
          = \frac{(0.617\;\text{mol})(0.082057\;\text{L·atm·K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1})(298.15\;\text{K})}{1\;\text{atm}}
          \approx 15.1\;\text{L}
\]

The pressure‑volume work is  

\[
w = -P\Delta V = -(1\;\text{atm})(15.1\;\text{L}) = -15.1\;\text{L·atm}
\]

Using \(1\;\text{L·atm}=101.325\;\text{J}\),

\[
w = -15.1\;\text{L·atm}\times 101.325\;\frac{\text{J}}{\text{L·atm}}
   \approx -1.53\times10^{3}\;\text{J}
   = -1.53\;\text{kJ}
\]

\[
\boxed{-1.53}\ \text{kJ}
\]

The molar heat capacity at constant pressure is  

\[
C_{p,m}= \frac{q}{n\Delta T}= \frac{229\ \text{J}}{3.0\ \text{mol}\times 2.55\ \text{K}}
      =\frac{229}{7.65}\ \text{J\,K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}
      \approx 29.9\ \text{J\,K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}.
\]

\[
\boxed{29.9}\ \mathrm{J\,K^{-1}\,mol^{-1}}
\]

The heat supplied at constant pressure is related to the molar heat capacity at constant pressure by  

\[
q = n\,C_{p,m}\,\Delta T \;\Longrightarrow\; 
C_{p,m}= \frac{q}{n\Delta T}
      = \frac{229\ \text{J}}{(3.0\ \text{mol})(2.55\ \text{K})}
      = 2.9934\times 10^{1}\ \frac{\text{J}}{\text{mol·K}} .
\]

For an ideal gas  

\[
C_{p,m}=C_{v,m}+R \;\Longrightarrow\; 
C_{v,m}=C_{p,m}-R .
\]

Using \(R = 8.314\ \text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}\),

\[
C_{v,m}= 29.93\ \frac{\text{J}}{\text{mol·K}} - 8.314\ \frac{\text{J}}{\text{mol·K}}
       = 21.6\ \frac{\text{J}}{\text{mol·K}} .
\]

\[
\boxed{21.6}\ \mathrm{J\,K^{-1}\,mol^{-1}}
\]

\[
\nu=\frac{c}{\lambda}= \frac{2.998\times10^{8}\ \text{m s}^{-1}}{632.8\times10^{-9}\ \text{m}}
      =4.74\times10^{14}\ \text{Hz}
\]

\[
\boxed{4.74}\times10^{14}\,\text{Hz}
\]

question:
$$
\text {Calculate the energy of a photon for a wavelength of } 100 \mathrm{pm} \text { (about one atomic diameter). }
$$

