The Bohr model gives the energy of a hydrogen‑like ion (charge \(Z\)) in the level \(n\)

\[
E_n=-\frac{Z^{2}R_{\!H}}{n^{2}},\qquad 
R_{\!H}=13.6\ \text{eV}
\]

For He\(^+\) (\(Z=2\)) in its ground state (\(n=1\))  

\[
E_{1}= -\frac{2^{2}\, (13.6\ \text{eV})}{1^{2}}
      =-4(13.6\ \text{eV})
      =-54.4\ \text{eV}
\]

The ionization energy is the energy needed to bring the electron from \(n=1\) to \(n=\infty\) (where \(E_\infty =0\)):

\[
\text{IE}=0-(-54.4\ \text{eV})=54.4\ \text{eV}
\]

Conversion to \(\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\) uses \(1\ \text{eV}=96.485\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\):

\[
\text{IE}=54.4\ \text{eV}\times 96.485\ \frac{\text{kJ}}{\text{mol·eV}}
        =5.2488\times10^{3}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{54.4}\ \text{eV}
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
\boxed{5.25\times10^{3}}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{-7.6\times10^{1}}\ \text{J}
\]

The calorimeter heat capacity is obtained from the benzoic‑acid calibration:

\[
\begin{aligned}
M_{\text{benzoic}} &= 122\;\text{g mol}^{-1}\\[2pt]
n_{\text{benzoic}} &=\frac{0.825\;\text{g}}{122\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}=6.77\times10^{-3}\;\text{mol}\\[2pt]
q_{\text{benzoic}} &= n_{\text{benzoic}}\;\Delta U_{\text{c}} 
                 = (6.77\times10^{-3}\,\text{mol})(-3251\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1})
                 = -22.0\;\text{kJ}\\[2pt]
C_{\text{cal}} &=\frac{-q_{\text{benzoic}}}{\Delta T}
               =\frac{22.0\;\text{kJ}}{1.940\;\text{K}}
               = 11.34\;\text{kJ K}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

For D‑ribose:

\[
\begin{aligned}
