The dissolution equilibrium is  

\[
\ce{PbS(s) <=> Pb^{2+} + S^{2-}},\qquad K_{sp}=9.0\times10^{-29}
\]

In the acidic solution the sulfide ion is protonated:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\ce{H2S &<=> H^{+} + HS^{-}} &K_{a1}=1.0\times10^{-7}\\
\ce{HS^{-} &<=> H^{+} + S^{2-}} &K_{a2}=1.0\times10^{-19}
\end{aligned}
\]

Hence  

\[
[S^{2-}] = \frac{K_{a1}K_{a2}[H_2S]}{[H^{+}]^{2}}
\]

Because the solution is strongly acidic, essentially all dissolved sulfide is present as \(\ce{H2S}\); therefore the molar solubility \(s\) equals \([\ce{Pb^{2+}}]=[H_2S]\).

Insert this into the solubility‑product expression:

\[
K_{sp}= [\ce{Pb^{2+}}][\ce{S^{2-}}]
      = s\left(\frac{K_{a1}K_{a2}s}{[H^{+}]^{2}}\right)
      =\frac{K_{a1}K_{a2}}{[H^{+}]^{2}}\,s^{2}
\]

Solve for \(s\):

\[
s = \sqrt{\frac{K_{sp}[H^{+}]^{2}}{K_{a1}K_{a2}}}
   = \sqrt{\frac{(9.0\times10^{-29})(0.30)^{2}}
                {(1.0\times10^{-7})(1.0\times10^{-19})}}
   = \sqrt{8.1\times10^{-4}}
   \approx 2.9\times10^{-2}
\]

\[
\boxed{2.9\times10^{-2}}\ \text{M}
\]

